If you want to delete error pods in one single command, here are the most useful options 👇


---

🔥 1. Delete all failed / error pods (all namespaces)

oc delete pod --field-selector=status.phase=Failed --all-namespaces


---

🔥 2. Delete CrashLoopBackOff / Error pods (most common case)

oc get pods --all-namespaces | grep -E 'Error|CrashLoopBackOff' | awk '{print "oc delete pod -n "$1" "$2}' | bash


---

🔥 3. Delete pods from a specific namespace

oc get pods -n <namespace> | grep -E 'Error|CrashLoopBackOff' | awk '{print "oc delete pod -n <namespace> "$1}' | bash

👉 Example:

oc get pods -n openshift-ovn-kubernetes | grep -E 'Error|CrashLoopBackOff' | awk '{print "oc delete pod -n openshift-ovn-kubernetes "$1}' | bash


---

⚠️ Important Notes

Pods will usually recreate automatically if controlled by:

Deployment

DaemonSet

StatefulSet


If root issue not fixed → pods will go back to error again



---

💡 Pro Tip (safer way)

First just list pods:

oc get pods -A | grep -E 'Error|CrashLoopBackOff'

Then delete.


---

🚀 One-liner (clean + safe)

oc get pods -A --no-headers | awk '$4 ~ /Error|CrashLoopBackOff/ {print "oc delete pod -n "$1" "$2}' | bash


